Diseases of Globalization
Globalization is being put to a severe test like never before.
His tensions grow everywhere.
The majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For supporters of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are his advantages apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
Certain regions have nevertheless gained only meager benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they are struggling with.
The slow growth of Africa, American leaders claim, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let us consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of government effectiveness (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations, and therefore large internal markets, tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples.)
Coastal countries tend to be more performant than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border wealthy markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more successful than those that are far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries do not care much about these structural problems, the gaps between the winners and the losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the responsibility onto unfortunate countries by claiming that they are somehow culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify instability.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by wealthy countries, and particularly the United States.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the basic needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their sufferings can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would indicate that the poorest countries are unable to raise sufficient funds to address such problems on their own.
Rather than watching wealthy countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that wealthy countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation in a striking manner.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing life-saving medicines and basic preventive services such as mosquito nets to combat malaria and vitamins to address nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount represents but a grain of sand for wealthy countries that systematically spend more than 2,000 dollars per person and per year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of just 200 dollars per person.
A healthcare system that works would cost more than the entire revenue of its government!
Even though Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases unless it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good physician would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that are hindering their economic growth and development.
In certain regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity in order to help these remote regions establish productive connections with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to funding these projects.
In Black Africa, the main challenges are disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main issues concern water scarcity, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all Washington consensus is outdated.
On the eve of the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinkers from the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
